 play, or television programme:\nShe\'s the highest-paid actress in Hollywood.',0,0,0),(16464,'actual','existing in fact:\nWe had estimated about 300 visitors, but the actual number was much higher.\nThe exams are in July, but the actual results (= the results themselves) don\'t appear until September.',0,0,0),(16465,'actually','in fact or really:\nI didn\'t actually see her - I just heard her voice.\nSo what actually happened?',0,0,0),(16466,'acute','If a bad situation is acute, it causes severe problems or damage:\nShe felt acute embarrassment/anxiety/concern at his behaviour.\nThe problem of poverty is particularly acute in rural areas.',0,0,0),(16467,'ad','informal for an advertisement:\nI often prefer the ads on TV to the actual programmes.',0,0,0),(16468,'adapt','to change, or to change something, to suit different conditions or uses:\nMany software companies have adapted popular programs to the new operating system.\nThe recipe here is a pork roast adapted from Caroline O\'Neill\'s book \"Louisiana Kitchen\".',0,0,0),(16469,'adaptation','the process of changing to suit different conditions:\nThe documentary is about corruption, crime and human adaptation to difficult circumstances.\nHis team\'s successful adaptation to life in the top-flight has come as no surprise.',0,0,0),(16470,'add','to put two or more numbers or amounts together to get a total:\nIf you add (= calculate the total of) three and four you get seven.\nIt\'s $45 - $50 if you add in (= include) the cost of postage.\nDon\'t forget to add on your travelling expenses/add your expenses on.',0,0,0),(16471,'addiction','an inability to stop doing or using something, especially something harmful:\ndrug addiction\nhis addiction to alcohol\nFor people with OCD, cleaning can become an addiction.',0,0,0),(16472,'addition','the process of adding numbers or amounts together:\nTwice a week the children are tested in basic mathematical skills such as addition (= calculating the total of different numbers put together) and subtraction.',0,0,0),(16473,'additional','extra:\nadditional costs/problems\nThere will be an extra charge for any additional passengers.',0,0,0),(16474,'additionally','also or in addition:\nAdditionally, we request a deposit of $200 in advance.\nYou can leave your pension in the fund, and additionally contribute to a personal pension.\nXem\nadditional',0,0,0),(16475,'address','the number of the house, name of the road, and name of the town where a person lives or works, and where letters can be sent:\nher business/home address\na change of address',0,0,0),(16476,'addressed','past simple and past participle of address',0,0,0),(16477,'adequate','enough or satisfactory for a particular purpose:\nHave we got adequate food for 20 guests?\nI didn\'t have adequate time to prepare.\nIt\'s not a big salary but it\'s adequate for our needs.\nThe council\'s provision for the elderly is barely adequate (= is not enough).',0,0,0),(16478,'adequately','in a way that is enough or satisfactory for a particular purpose:\nWhile some patients can be adequately cared for at home, others are best served by care in a hospital.\nManufacturers may lack the means to adequately test their product.',0,0,0),(16479,'adhere','to stick firmly:\nA smooth, dry surface helps the tiles adhere to the wall.',0,0,0),(16480,'adjacent','very near, next to, or touching:\nThey work in adjacent buildings.\nThey lived in a house adjacent to the railway.',0,0,0),(16481,'adjunct','formal\nsomething added or connected to a larger or more important thing:\nI hoped I would find the computer course a useful adjunct to my other studies.',0,0,0),(16482,'adjust','to change something slightly, especially to make it more correct, effective, or suitable:\nIf the chair is too high you can adjust it to suit you.\nAs a teacher you have to adjust your methods to suit the needs of slower children.',0,0,0),(16483,'adjustment','a small change:\nShe made a few minor adjustments to the focus of her camera.',0,0,0),(16484,'administer','(also administrate, UK/ədˈmɪn.ɪ.streɪt/ US/ədˈmɪn.ə.streɪt/)\nto control the operation or arrangement of something:\nThe economy has been badly administered by the present government.',0,0,0),(16485,'administration','(informal admin, UK  /ˈæd.mɪn/ US  /ˈæd.mɪn/)\nthe arrangements and tasks needed to control the operation of a plan or organization:\nTeachers complain that more of their time is taken up with administration than with teaching.\nShe has little experience in admin (= in organizing a business, etc.).',0,0,0),(16486,'administrative','relating to the arrangements and work that is needed to control the operation of a plan or organization:\nadministrative work\nan administrative problem\nYour responsibilities will be mainly administrative.',0,0,0),(16487,'administrator','someone whose job is to control the operation of a business, organization, or plan:\nFrom 1969 to 1971, he was administrator of the Illinois state drug abuse program.\nShe works as a school administrator.',0,0,0),(16488,'admire','to find someone or something attractive and pleasant to look at:\nWe stood for a few moments, admiring the view.\nI was just admiring your jacket, Delia.',0,0,0),(16489,'admission','the act of agreeing that something is true, especially unwillingly:\nHer silence was taken as an admission of guilt/defeat.',0,0,0),(16490,'admit','to agree that something is true, especially unwillingly:\nHe admitted his guilt/mistake.',0,0,0),(16491,'adolescent','a young person who is developing into an adult',0,0,0),(16492,'adopt','to legally take another person\'s child into your own family and take care of him or her as your own child:\nThey\'ve adopted a baby girl.\nShe had the child adopted (= she gave her baby to someone else to take care of).\nThey have no children of their own, but they\'re hoping to adopt.',0,0,0),(16493,'adoption','the act of legally taking a child to be taken care of as your own:\nShe was homeless and had to put her child up for adoption (=